.TH SEATUYA 3 "2026-03-06" "seatuya 0.1.0" "Library Functions Manual"
.SH NAME
seatuya \- C library for local control of Tuya smart devices
.SH SYNOPSIS
.B #include <seatuya/seatuya.h>
.PP
.BI "const char *seatuya_version(void);"
.PP
.BI "seatuya_device_t *seatuya_create(const char *" version ");"
.br
.BI "void seatuya_destroy(seatuya_device_t *" dev ");"
.PP
.BI "bool seatuya_connect(seatuya_device_t *" dev ", const char *" hostname ");"
.br
.BI "void seatuya_disconnect(seatuya_device_t *" dev ");"
.br
.BI "bool seatuya_is_connected(seatuya_device_t *" dev ");"
.PP
.BI "bool seatuya_negotiate_session(seatuya_device_t *" dev ", const char *" key ");"
.br
.BI "bool seatuya_negotiate_session_start(seatuya_device_t *" dev ", const char *" key ");"
.br
.BI "bool seatuya_negotiate_session_finalize(seatuya_device_t *" dev ","
.BI "    unsigned char *" buf ", int " size ", const char *" key ");"
.PP
.BI "int seatuya_build_message(seatuya_device_t *" dev ", unsigned char *" buf ","
.BI "    enum seatuya_command " cmd ", const char *" payload ", const char *" key ");"
.br
.BI "char *seatuya_decode_message(seatuya_device_t *" dev ", unsigned char *" buf ","
.BI "    int " size ", const char *" key ");"
.br
.BI "char *seatuya_generate_payload(seatuya_device_t *" dev ","
.BI "    enum seatuya_command " cmd ", const char *" device_id ","
.BI "    const char *" datapoints ");"
.PP
.BI "int seatuya_send(seatuya_device_t *" dev ", unsigned char *" buf ", int " size ");"
.br
.BI "int seatuya_receive(seatuya_device_t *" dev ", unsigned char *" buf ","
.BI "    int " maxsize ", int " minsize ");"
.PP
.BI "void seatuya_free_string(char *" str ");"
.PP
.BI "void seatuya_set_async_mode(seatuya_device_t *" dev ", bool " async ");"
.br
.BI "bool seatuya_is_socket_readable(seatuya_device_t *" dev ");"
.br
.BI "bool seatuya_is_socket_writable(seatuya_device_t *" dev ");"
.br
.BI "bool seatuya_set_session_ready(seatuya_device_t *" dev ");"
.PP
.BI "enum seatuya_protocol seatuya_get_protocol(seatuya_device_t *" dev ");"
.br
.BI "enum seatuya_session_state seatuya_get_session_state(seatuya_device_t *" dev ");"
.br
.BI "enum seatuya_socket_state seatuya_get_socket_state(seatuya_device_t *" dev ");"
.br
.BI "int seatuya_get_last_error(seatuya_device_t *" dev ");"
.SH DESCRIPTION
.B seatuya
is a C wrapper around the tuyapp C++ library.
It provides a stable C ABI for communicating with Tuya / Smart Life
devices on the local network, supporting protocol versions 3.1, 3.3,
3.4, and 3.5.
.PP
The existing Tuya libraries are language-specific: tuyapp requires C++,
and tinytuya requires Python.
.B seatuya
exposes the same functionality through a plain C interface with no C++
types crossing the ABI boundary: opaque struct pointers, C strings,
ints, and enums.
Any language with a foreign-function interface (FFI) can link against
.B libseatuya
and control Tuya devices directly, without embedding a C++ runtime
or a Python interpreter.
.SS Lifecycle
.BR seatuya_create ()
allocates a device handle for the given protocol version
("3.1", "3.3", "3.4", or "3.5").
Returns NULL on invalid version.
The handle must be freed with
.BR seatuya_destroy ().
.SS Connection
.BR seatuya_connect ()
opens a TCP connection to the device on port 6668.
For protocol 3.4 and above, call
.BR seatuya_negotiate_session ()
after connecting to establish an encrypted session.
For 3.1 and 3.3, session negotiation is a no-op.
.SS Async mode
By default, receive calls block.
.BR seatuya_set_async_mode ()
enables non-blocking operation.
When async mode is on,
.BR seatuya_receive ()
returns immediately with \-1 if no data is available, and
.BR seatuya_is_socket_readable ()
can be used to poll.
For protocol 3.4+, call
.BR seatuya_set_session_ready ()
after async negotiation completes.
.SS Session negotiation
Protocol versions 3.4 and 3.5 require a key-exchange handshake before
encrypted communication can begin.
.BR seatuya_negotiate_session ()
performs this in a single blocking call.
For async workflows, use
.BR seatuya_negotiate_session_start ()
to send the initial handshake, then call
.BR seatuya_negotiate_session_finalize ()
with the device's response.
.SS Messages
.BR seatuya_build_message ()
encrypts and frames a JSON payload for transmission.
.BR seatuya_decode_message ()
decrypts a received response.
Both require the device's local encryption key (a 16-byte hex string
from the Tuya cloud).
.PP
.BR seatuya_generate_payload ()
builds the JSON payload structure expected by the device for a given
command and set of data points.
.PP
Strings returned by
.BR seatuya_decode_message ()
and
.BR seatuya_generate_payload ()
are heap-allocated and must be freed with
.BR seatuya_free_string ().
.SS State queries
.BR seatuya_get_protocol (),
.BR seatuya_get_session_state (),
.BR seatuya_get_socket_state (),
and
.BR seatuya_get_last_error ()
return the current state of the device handle.
.SH RETURN VALUES
.BR seatuya_connect (),
.BR seatuya_negotiate_session (),
and related session functions return
.B true
on success and
.B false
on failure.
.PP
.BR seatuya_build_message ()
returns the message size in bytes, or \-1 on error.
.PP
.BR seatuya_send ()
and
.BR seatuya_receive ()
return byte counts, or \-1 on error.
.SH EXAMPLES
Connect to a device and turn on data point 1:
.PP
.RS
.nf
seatuya_device_t *dev = seatuya_create("3.4");
seatuya_connect(dev, "192.168.1.100");
seatuya_negotiate_session(dev, local_key);

char *payload = seatuya_generate_payload(dev,
    SEATUYA_CMD_CONTROL, device_id, "{\\"1\\":true}");
unsigned char buf[1024];
int n = seatuya_build_message(dev, buf,
    SEATUYA_CMD_CONTROL, payload, local_key);
seatuya_free_string(payload);

seatuya_send(dev, buf, n);
n = seatuya_receive(dev, buf, sizeof buf, 0);
char *response = seatuya_decode_message(dev, buf, n, local_key);
printf("%s\\n", response);
seatuya_free_string(response);

seatuya_destroy(dev);
.fi
.RE
.PP
The same workflow can be replicated from any language with FFI.
The newLISP bindings shipped with seatuya (seatuya.lsp) demonstrate
this: a thin module wraps the entire C API, and the example
programs (seatuya-wizard.lsp, sousvide-ramp.lsp) use it to control
real hardware without writing any C.
.SS newLISP convenience layer
.B seatuya.lsp
also provides high-level functions that collapse the five-step
send/receive round-trip into a single call.
Store credentials once with
.BR tuya:set-credentials ,
then use
.BR tuya:set-value
and
.BR tuya:status
without passing device-id and local-key on every call:
.PP
.RS
.nf
(load "seatuya.lsp")
(setq dev (tuya:create "3.3"))
(tuya:connect dev "192.168.1.50")
(tuya:set-credentials dev device-id local-key)
(tuya:set-value dev 1 true)     ; turn on DP 1
(tuya:status dev)                ; query all DPs
(tuya:destroy dev)
.fi
.RE
.SS newLISP FOOP device classes
.B tuya-devices.lsp
provides device-class convenience functions using newLISP FOOP
(Functional Object-Oriented Programming), mirroring the device
classes in tinytuya.
Each class maps named methods to the correct data point numbers
for that device category:
.PP
.RS
.nf
(load "tuya-devices.lsp")

; Smart plug
(setq plug (OutletDevice "3.3" "192.168.1.50" dev-id key))
(:turn-on plug)
(:turn-off plug)
(:destroy plug)

; RGB bulb (type B)
(setq bulb (BulbDevice "3.4" "192.168.1.51" dev-id key))
(:set-colour bulb 255 0 0)
(:set-brightness-pct bulb 50)
(:destroy bulb)
.fi
.RE
.PP
Available classes:
.BR OutletDevice
(smart plugs, power strips),
.BR BulbDevice
(RGB/RGBW bulbs, type A and B DP layouts),
.BR CoverDevice
(blinds, curtains, garage doors -- 8 command variants),
.BR ThermostatDevice
(thermostats, HVAC -- configurable DP map),
.BR FanDevice
(fans, air purifiers),
.BR LockDevice ,
and
.BR SirenDevice .
All classes support
.B :status
(query DPs),
.B :reconnect
(re-establish a dropped connection, including session negotiation
for protocol 3.4+), and
.B :destroy
(disconnect and free).
Constructor arguments allow overriding default DP numbers
for devices with non-standard mappings.
.SH CONSTANTS
.TP
.B SEATUYA_DEFAULT_PORT
6668 (Tuya local protocol port).
.TP
.B SEATUYA_RECOMMENDED_BUFSIZE
1024 bytes.
